<p>A typical residential solar installation in Pennsylvania can be expected to produce between 1,100-1,300 kWh per installed kW annually. This means a standard 8kW residential system would generate approximately 8,800-10,400 kWh per year, which closely matches the average Pennsylvania household's annual electricity consumption of 9,500-11,000 kWh. Solar production follows seasonal patterns, with peak generation occurring during summer months (May through August) and reduced production during winter months due to shorter days and increased cloud cover.</p>

<p>The state's net metering policies allow homeowners to sell excess solar production back to their utility at retail rates, providing credits that can offset electricity consumption during periods of low solar production. This policy framework, combined with Pennsylvania's renewable energy standards, creates a favorable environment for residential solar adoption and helps maximize the financial benefits of solar investments.</p>

