<h2>Pennsylvania Incentives & Rebates</h2>

<p>Pennsylvania homeowners have access to several valuable incentives that significantly reduce the cost of solar panel and HVAC system installations. The federal Investment Tax Credit (ITC) provides a 30% tax credit for solar installations completed through 2032, with the credit stepping down to 26% in 2033 and 22% in 2034. This credit applies to the total system cost, including equipment, installation, permits, and related expenses, making it one of the most valuable solar incentives available.</p>

<p>The state's Solar Alternative Energy Credit (SAEC) program provides ongoing financial benefits for solar system owners. For every 1,000 kWh of solar electricity generated, homeowners receive one SAEC, which can be sold to utility companies to help them meet renewable energy requirements. SAEC prices fluctuate based on market conditions but typically range from \$10-40 per credit, providing additional income that improves the overall return on investment for solar installations.</p>

<p>PECO Energy offers several rebate programs for energy-efficient HVAC equipment and solar installations. Their Smart A/C Saver program provides rebates up to \$100 for ENERGY STAR certified air conditioning systems, while their Smart Heat Pump program offers rebates up to \$500 for qualifying heat pump installations. PECO also provides interconnection support and net metering services for solar customers, streamlining the installation process and ensuring proper system integration with the electrical grid.</p>

<p>Local municipalities and counties throughout Pennsylvania may offer additional incentives, property tax exemptions, or expedited permitting for renewable energy and energy efficiency projects. Many utility companies beyond PECO, including PPL Electric Utilities and Duquesne Light, offer similar rebate programs and energy efficiency incentives. Additionally, financing options such as Property Assessed Clean Energy (PACE) programs may be available in certain areas, allowing homeowners to finance improvements through property tax assessments.</p>

